======================================================================
PART 3: CONVEXITY OF log prod(1+Q)
======================================================================

log prod(1+Q_k) = sum log(1+Q_k)
log(1+x) is CONCAVE. So by Jensen: sum log(1+Q_k) <= m*log(1+mean(Q))
The FLAT distribution (Paley) would maximize this!
But Interval wins... so something deeper is happening.

  p=7, m=3:
    sum log(1+Q) Interval = 2.564949
    sum log(1+Q) Paley    = 3.034803
    Jensen upper bound     = 3.295837
    Interval / Paley ratio = 0.625094
    Interval log-advantage = -0.469853
    Lower bound (AM-GM): 2^m = 8
    prod(1+Q_Int) = 13.0

  p=11, m=5:
    sum log(1+Q) Interval = 4.488636
    sum log(1+Q) Paley    = 6.608779
    Jensen upper bound     = 6.931472
    Interval / Paley ratio = 0.120014
    Interval log-advantage = -2.120143
    Lower bound (AM-GM): 2^m = 32
    prod(1+Q_Int) = 89.0

  p=13, m=6:
    sum log(1+Q) Interval = 5.451038
    sum log(1+Q) Paley    = 8.499640
    Jensen upper bound     = 9.024464
    Interval / Paley ratio = 0.047425
    Interval log-advantage = -3.048602
    Lower bound (AM-GM): 2^m = 64
    prod(1+Q_Int) = 233.0

  p=17, m=8:
    sum log(1+Q) Interval = 7.375882
    sum log(1+Q) Paley    = 13.032386
    Jensen upper bound     = 13.637985
    Interval / Paley ratio = 0.003495
    Interval log-advantage = -5.656504
    Lower bound (AM-GM): 2^m = 256
    prod(1+Q_Int) = 1597.0

  p=23, m=11:
    sum log(1+Q) Interval = 10.263153
    sum log(1+Q) Paley    = 21.004968
    Jensen upper bound     = 21.405012
    Interval / Paley ratio = 0.000022
    Interval log-advantage = -10.741815
    Lower bound (AM-GM): 2^m = 2048
    prod(1+Q_Int) = 28657.0


  KEY INSIGHT: Although log(1+x) is concave, the constraint
  prod(Q_k) = 1 combined with e_j = C(m+j, 2j) forces the
  product to equal F_p for Interval, which EXCEEDS the flat bound!

  This is because the Q_k satisfy a system of polynomial equations
  (the Morgan-Voyce constraints), not just prod=1 and sum=m(m+1)/2.

